Part 2

The hospital corridor smelled of Dettol and overcooked rice from the visitors' canteen.

Vikram found the room by counting doors, not by asking anyone.

His father was not sitting up reading files.

That version of this scene existed only in the ones Vikram had built on the train.

The real one: Binay Ahuja lay propped on two flat pillows, skin gone the color of weak tea, a saline line taped crooked into the back of his hand.

Awake.

Watching the door.

"You came," Binay said.

Not a question.

"Papa."

"Sit."

Vikram sat.

For a while neither of them said the thing that needed saying, and instead said the things that fill the space before it.

"Rohan ate?"

"I don't know, Papa."

"Someone should check."

"I'll check."

"Sit first."

Vikram sat back down.

A young resident doctor came in, flipped a chart, said words like *portal hypertension* and *we'll monitor* and *let's see how he responds* in the tone doctors use when they don't yet know which sentence they'll need to say next week.

Vikram, second year, understood exactly enough of the words to know that not knowing was the actual diagnosis.

The resident left.

Binay watched him go.

"He talks like your professors," Binay said. "Confident about being unsure."

"That's the job, Papa."

"Was going to be your job too."

Vikram said nothing.

"I told Sharma-ji at the club last year.

My son, wait and watch, one day, big doctor.

I said it like it was already sitting in my pocket."

He looked at the saline line in his own hand like it belonged to someone else.

"Seems fate had a different item in that pocket."

"Papa, don't—"

"I'm not being dramatic.

I'm being accurate."

A silence that had weight to it.

Then Binay did something Vikram didn't expect.

He looked almost embarrassed.

"I have to ask you something and I don't like asking it."

"Ask."

"Can you stay some weeks.

Just to look after things at the office.

Nothing big.

Sign what Pradhan-babu tells you to sign.

Rohan is sixteen, still in school, can't be there every day."

"Some weeks," Vikram repeated.

"That's all I'm asking."

It did not feel like all he was asking.

It felt like the first sentence of something much longer, spoken deliberately small so it could be agreed to.

Vikram said yes anyway.

What else does a nineteen-year-old say to a father with a tube in his hand.

---

Pradhan-babu turned out to be sixty-one years old, wore the same brown cardigan every day regardless of weather, and had worked for Binay Ahuja since before Vikram was born.

His office was one room, one ceiling fan missing a blade, and a typewriter that jammed on the letter 'M'.

"Sign here, sign here, and here," he told Vikram the first morning, sliding three ledgers across.

Vikram signed.

"Not like that."

"Like what?"

"Full signature.

Not initials.

Bank won't accept initials from a new signatory."

Vikram signed again, slower, the letters coming out wrong-sized, a schoolboy's hand trying to look official.

Pradhan-babu watched him do it twice more before it looked acceptable.

Didn't comment.

Just refiled the ledger.

At noon, a factory supervisor from the malt unit came to the office, twisting his cap in both hands, waiting to speak to "Ahuja Sahib."

Vikram stood to greet him properly, the way you greet a senior doctor doing rounds.

"Sir," Vikram said, before he could stop himself.

The supervisor blinked.

Looked behind him to check who Vikram was addressing.

Nobody was there.

Pradhan-babu, from his desk, without looking up: "You're Ahuja Sahib now.

People say sir to you.

Not the other way."

Vikram felt his ears go warm, the exact same warmth from a different room, a different year, a stitched name on an apron.

He straightened.

Tried again.

"Yes, tell me. What's the problem at the unit?"

Better.

Not good.

Better.

---

Some weeks became six weeks.

Six weeks became a semester he didn't return for.

Binay came home from the hospital thinner than before, walking slower, but home — the crisis, whatever it truly was, had loosened its grip without fully letting go.

He never again mentioned the boy who was going to wear a white coat.

Vikram never again mentioned the exam he'd missed, then the one after.

Some things are easier to leave unfinished than to formally end.

The pathology textbook stayed behind in a hostel two hundred kilometers away, in a friend's cupboard neither of them thought about often.

The signature got better.

The "sir" stopped catching in his throat.

Nobody in that office remembered, within a year, that he had ever hesitated.

Vikram remembered.

He just stopped mentioning it.
